positive.review:
I love this game, but before you get into the Korean brain-rot cult that is the Project Moon Universe, there are lots of pros and cons to this game, it ain't perfect, after all.

Limbus Company is a side-sequel to Lobotomy Corporation and Library of Ruina, it is recommended to play both games to get more insight about the Universe and some terminologies, but not required, I'd say that this game by itself can be a good enough explanation to it all.

-+-
THE GACHA ELEPHANT IN THE ROOM:
Yes, this game IS a gacha, there's absolutely no denying it, although it doesn't hinder the game in any way, it is a vital element of it, but you don't always need the shiny new stuff to get through.
The way it's put is by having the same 12 characters being possessed by their Mirror Worlds(parallel universes) counterparts, that way you can still use the characters you like(I much prefer this as opposed to just pulling for new characters).
In my opinion, I think it's implemented quite well, you do not need to ever spend any money in it, has good rates(compared to other gachas), a good "pity" system, and most important of all: no FOMO, all past identities can be acquired for free, at any time, with no truly Limited Runs(apart from the recent Arknights Collab).
Another feature from this is that the investment put into the game is actually noticeable, with later identities and chapters having fancier animations and such.
The only complaint I have about this feature is the massive discrepancy between early and later IDs, sometimes making it harder to use the ones you like, due to the huge numbers gap and some later IDs being straight up busted(also, it would be nice to be able to use the base IDs on later chapters).
-+-

Pros:
+The highlight of the game is it's story, with some interesting and odd world building, it does absolutely get better along the way, in both writing and presentation;
+Good art style;
+The fights, although simple for the most part, have nice animations, having very "impactful" hits and satisfactory sound design;
+Great combat system, being a streamlined version of Library of Ruina's one, it still keeps the engaging mechanics and incentivized team building;
+Likeable characters that get fleshed out in their respective chapters;
+Great music and voice acting;
+The game does not require any massive amounts of grinding at all, especially when the Hard Mirror Dungeon is unlocked;
+Related to the point above, it has a very generous gacha system.

Cons:
-The game is a visual novel, it's emphasis is in dialogue, but, due to budgetary issues, it was made with single body sprites(only having the faces change), though it might sound like a pet peeve, it CAN be very annoying and take away from some story beats, it certainly would be nicer to have different character sprites and/or more usage CGs instead(wich is a trend that the later chapters are starting to pick up on, but the early ones are left outdated), now that Project Moon isn't that strapped for cash anymore;
-The world building can feel very one-dimensional at times;
-Most of the side characters are really flat, especially at earlier chapters, where most of them are just fodder;
-The Chain Battles are very repetitive and not as engaging as the Focused Encounters, the fight highlights are absolutely the Bosses, but it takes a lot of Chain Battles to get there;

-+-
Despite these flaws, I still recommend the game, it's free after all, so should be worth a shot. Two big thumbs up, would give it more if I had more thumbs.
